@Generated(value="com.guidewire.pl.metadata.codegen.Codegen", comments="Address.eti;Address.eix;Address.etx") public class Address extends com.guidewire.pl.persistence.code.BeanBase implements AddressAutofillable, AddressBookLinkable, Retireable, Extractable, OverlapTable, Obfuscatable, AddressHandlingMethods, Obfuscator
Address

Represents a street or mailing address. Addresses are normally associated with a Contact, either as a Contact.PrimaryAddress or via the ContactAddress table. Addresses can have geographic location information stored for proximity searches.

invalid reference 
com.guidewire.pl.domain.contact.Contact
invalid reference

      public List<Address> getCorrectionsFromGeocodingPlugin()
      This gets a list of addresses which could match the provided address. The first result in the list is used as the best match found. This caps the number of results found.

      You can check if this is supported with a call to GeocodeUtils.currentPluginSupportsMultipleCorrections()

      Returns:
      A list of addresses. The first result returned will be the best match available.

    • getCorrectionsFromGeocodingPlugin

      public List<Address> getCorrectionsFromGeocodingPlugin(int maxResults)
      This gets a list of addresses which could match the provided address. The first result in the list is used as the best match found. This caps the number of results found.

      Note that this DOES NOT modify the original address; if you want to use this in lieu of regular geocoding (ie geocodeSynchronously) you will have to copy over SpatialPoint and GeocodeStatus from the selected match.

      You can check if this is supported with a call to GeocodeUtils.currentPluginSupportsMultipleCorrections()

      Parameters:
      maxResults - the maximum number of results to return, if a positive/non-zero integer. Returns all results if zero or negative.
      Returns:
      A list of addresses. The first result returned will be the best match available.

    • getPublicID

      public String getPublicID()
      The external ID for this entity.

      PublicID values are automatically created during the commit, if not previously set. The format is random, meeting security requirements based on current industry standards. For example:

      • pc:SYinDB2XTOgNZFs1NpxU8
      • pc:Sf8QS4N5RBS-h8_pj-Oy_
      • pc:SBwBzylneecSNr6_Ub4IO
      Your configuration code must not assume any particular format for PublicID values, in either the prefix or body portion of the string, or even assume the existence of a prefix. Do not make any assumptions at all about the content of a PublicID value, including expectations that values are sequential, numeric, or prefixed.

      You can subclass and override AbstractBundleTransactionCallback.afterSetIds(gw.pl.persistence.core.Bundle) if you need to see the value in the same commit. 

      
  var note = new Note(bundle)
  bundle.addBundleTransactionCallback(new AbstractBundleTransactionCallback() {
     override function afterSetIds(b : Bundle) {
       log.info("Created Note " + note.PublicID)
     }
  })
      Specified by:
      getPublicID in interface Editable
      Specified by:
      getPublicID in interface KeyableBean
      Specified by:
      getPublicID in interface Retireable
      Specified by:
      getPublicID in interface Versionable
      Returns:
      the external id.

    • setPublicID

      public void setPublicID(String id)
      Sets the external id for this entity. *
        *
      • Do not change the publicID once it is exposed externally.
        • *
      • The publicID must be unique.
        • *
      • The publicID must not leak information.
        • *
      * If you do not set the publicID manually, then it is automatically set upon commit. * For increased security, the default value is random. If you manually set the value, ensure that it is similarly secure and unique.

    • touch

      public void touch()
      Set's the version of the bean to the next value (i.e. the bean version original value+1) Multiple calls to this method on the same bean will result in the same value being used for the version (i.e. it is idempotent). Calling this method will force the bean to be written to the database and participate fully in the commit cycle e.g. pre-update rules will be run, etc.
